          <div class="content-container">
            <h3>Usage</h3>
            <p>Contains all the elements needed to build forms.</p>
            <h4>Interactions</h4>
            <p>Form elements will displayed default browser interactions such as focus or highlight states. We recommend and HTML 5 doctype and the use of as many HTML 5 form type attributes as possible for helping users receive client side validation guidance.</p>
            <h4>Layout modes</h4>
            <p>There is only a single layout mode for form elements. We recommend only display form elements with the label stacked vertically above. We woudl not recommend implementing form pages with a label placed horizontally. This will cause problems on lower width screens.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>CSS</h3>
            <p>Only common styles are loaded for this component.</p>
            <h4>SASS Partials</h4>
            <p>You can find the CSS for this component in the following SASS Partials:</p>
            <p>/common/forms.scss</p>
            <p>The majority of the form styles reside within the Twitter Bootstrap framework</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Use of JavaScript</h3>
            <p>The datepicker element is implemented with the <a href="http://www.eyecon.ro/bootstrap-datepicker/">bootstrap-datepicker.js</a> library. </p>
            <h4>Non-JS behaviour</h4>
            <p>The datepicker form field will default to a standard text input if javascript is not available.</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Component variants</h3>
            <p>We have supplied an example of all of the form components contained within the Twitter Bootstrap framework and a couple of custom items we detected within the clubcard site, such as captcha and date selectors. Any permutation of form layout should be possible with the supplied form elements</p>
            <hr />
            <h3>Accessibility</h3>
            <p>Form elements should always be associated correctly with the label for tag to describe their purpose. Fieldsets can be used to group form elements but should be used sparingly and contain very little copy as screenreaders will prefix every form element with the fieldset text. </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
